<p>
<seg id="1">Joint report on the parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the Prague motorway - Dresden Preliminary remark Without trans-European motorways, modern, united Europe could only cope with the high volume of traffic between the partner countries with considerable restrictions and quality losses.</seg>
<seg id="2">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="3">High-quality transport networks are indispensable for maintaining and increasing living standards in Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Ensuring fast, safe, reliable and economical passenger and freight transport is an important task for the state.</seg>
<seg id="5">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="6">It requires a high degree of organisational, technical and financial effort.</seg>
<seg id="7">When building and developing a sustainable European transport infrastructure, difficult compromises often have to be made with European and national political objectives, such as the preservation of the environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">It is precisely because of the necessary environmental protection measures that the construction of the transport infrastructure is complex.</seg>
<seg id="9">When planning and awarding the construction of transport routes, administrations can save considerable financial resources through careful action and decision-making and use them for other useful purposes.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of state audit authorities is to identify deficiencies that preclude optimum economy, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness in expenditure on the construction of transport facilities.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit authorities should not only alert administrations to the shortcomings identified, but also make suggestions for improvements for the benefit of citizens and for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two Supreme Audit Authorities of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic, the Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) and the Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad (NKò), carried out parallel audits of expenditure for the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (motorway D 8 in the Czech Republic and motorway A 17 in the Federal Republic of Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The two motorways are connected by a border bridge jointly financed by both states.</seg>
<seg id="15">The cooperation with the NKò enabled the BRH to carry out an in-depth examination of the cost-effectiveness of the use of funds in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">In the course of its cooperation with the BRH, the NKò received data from German bridges and tunnels for its own cost comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany signed a contract for the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the planning progress, the date of completion was finally set for the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">During the award procedure, however, the Road and Motorway Directorate of the Czech Republic (RMD) made errors that delayed the procedure and shortened the available construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was therefore concluded later than planned.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor assured the accelerated construction of the bridge by the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">However, the RMD had to accept considerable additional costs.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint audit activity, the prices of motorway bridges on the D 8 and the A 17 were compared. The benchmark for the price comparison of the bridges was the size of the bridge area.</seg>
<seg id="24">A price analysis using statistical methods identified bridges with high costs per square metre.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis showed that the border bridge under the large bridges with lengths of over 100 m was the most expensive.</seg>
<seg id="26">This was also due to the price increase as a result of the delays in the award.</seg>
<seg id="27">The comparison of the prices of the tunnels showed that the prices of the tunnels in the course of the D 8 are considerably higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">In future audits of the profitability of expenditure on transport infrastructure, both BRH and NKò can rely on a data collection of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="29">Both courts of auditors recommend standardizing bridge structures and carrying out steel composite and special structures only where prestressed concrete structures are inappropriate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The course of the examination was characterized by teamwork and an open approach.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel examination, the examiners from both sides exchanged their expertise and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of this report is the parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the motorway from Dresden to Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The audit focused on economy, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness of the use of funds.</seg>
<seg id="35">The parallel tests were conducted by the BRH in Germany and the NKò in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="36">in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The NKò examined the economy, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness of the expenditure for the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway in the amount of approximately 20 billion CZK gross (approximately €690 million).</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, €64 million will be allocated from EU Structural Funds (ISPA).</seg>
<seg id="39">Independently of the parallel tests with the NKò, the BRH had already examined the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway between 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">Of the financial volume for the construction of all three sections of the A 17 of approximately €670 million, €277 million will be co-financed by European Funds (ERDF).</seg>
<seg id="41">The Prague-Dresden motorway is part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV Dresden - Central and Southeastern Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 runs from Prague via Usti nad Labem to the Czech / German border,</seg>
<seg id="43">the A 17 from the border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the inspection, the border sections of the motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">Both sections were opened to traffic on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">While the motorway is thus completed on the German side to Dresden, the D 8 remains incomplete on the Czech side, as the section 0805 over a length of 16.4 km between Rehlovice and Lovosice is still in the planning phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">Here the crossing of a protected landscape area in the Bohemian Central Uplands is planned.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to Czech forecasts from 2001, traffic in 2008 in the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway will amount to 22 940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="49">German forecasts estimate the volume of traffic on the A 17 at the Czech border in 2010 at around 25,000 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic concluded a contract for the merger of the German motorway A 17 and the Czech motorway D 8 at the common state border by building a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Since both states are involved in the construction of this bridge, this individual construction project represented an important aspect of the parallel audits of both courts of auditors.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and NKò</seg>
<seg id="53">From mid-2005, both courts of auditors made joint considerations on cooperation in the examination of the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had important reasons for this cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany is partly financing the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Planning and construction are the responsibility of the Czech Road Construction Administration.</seg>
<seg id="58">There was no possibility for the BRH to examine this construction project itself.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The NKò had no comparative data to assess whether the funds were used sparingly with regard to the total construction costs of the bridges and tunnels on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The NKò also had to examine the effectiveness of the expenditure by examining the essential technical parameters of the bridges and tunnels, which should ensure the same quality of use on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">After preparatory negotiations, the Presidents of the two Court of Auditors concluded an agreement on the coordination of the audits of the Prague-Dresden motorway on 4 January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="64">The auditors of both courts of auditors met at intervals of about six to eight weeks in the course of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="65">They dealt with current problems and tasks. They developed a uniform methodology for testing bridge and tunnel prices, exchanged test results for the construction of the border bridge and prepared joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">Essential to the cooperation was the ongoing exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="67">While the BRH devoted itself primarily to the comparison of the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels as well as the award procedures, the NKò mainly developed the methodology for the analysis of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="68">In Germany and the Czech Republic, the legal basis for financial control differs and thus also the way in which the two courts of auditors complete their audits.</seg>
<seg id="69">Therefore, both authorities prepared separate national reports on their audit results.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report takes into account the results of the two parallel tests.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation ends with the signing of a final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In the 2000 treaty, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed to complete the border bridge in 2005 if possible.</seg>
<seg id="74">They later postponed the date by mutual agreement until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD acted as the client of the construction project.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany contributes 42.13% to the construction of the bridge.</seg>
<seg id="77">Initially, the RMD envisaged a prestressed concrete construction for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="78">However, the RMD agreed with its German partner in 1999 on the construction of a steel composite structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">They justified this decision with the possible reduction of the number of pillar pairs from seven to five and the associated ecological benefits for the floodplain.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, a comparative calculation of the RMD had shown the steel composite structure as the more cost-effective solution.</seg>
<seg id="81">However, this was due to a calculation error.</seg>
<seg id="82">The calculation assumed a length of the new steel composite structure of only 397 m,</seg>
<seg id="83">In fact, it is 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the award procedure, the RMD made serious errors,</seg>
<seg id="85">by insufficiently preparing the award documents and inaccurately describing both evaluation criteria and sub-criteria.</seg>
<seg id="86">These errors led to subjective and ambiguous assessments of the evaluation commission and the director general of the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="87">A losing bidder challenged the outcome of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">The subsequent investigation by the Czech Antitrust Office delayed the signing of the construction contract for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="89">As a result, the summer construction season following the bid review was lost in 2004 and the total construction time available was shortened.</seg>
<seg id="90">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time, resulting in a significant price increase.</seg>
<seg id="91">Among the measures offered were the double assembly of the superstructures, the change of the pillar shape and the construction of an assembly hall.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the contractor was unable to procure the originally intended type of steel.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new type of steel - whose higher costs of around €4 million were borne by the client alone - made it possible to shorten the construction time planned for corrosion protection and thus the total construction time.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the offer price of approximately €18.3 million net, the acceleration measures and further supplements will significantly increase the total construction costs of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="95">The shortened construction period alone led to a price increase of approximately €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">Without price sliding, the costs are currently around €25.9 million net (as of October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of prices of bridges and tunnels</seg>
<seg id="98">Both courts of auditors examined the bridge prices on the D 8 and the A 17 in order to identify the bridges, which were characterized by particularly high prices and to compare bridge prices on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The study was based on mathematical statistical methods.</seg>
<seg id="100">The tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on the German motorways A 71, A 38 and A 4, as there were no comparable tunnels on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="101">In preparing this part of the exam, a precise definition of the price concept was important.</seg>
<seg id="102">For the comparison of bridge prices, both courts of auditors agreed on detailed specifications, such as: to use the current price paid for the bridge without VAT.</seg>
<seg id="103">(VAT rates in the Czech Republic and Germany vary and may change), not to take into account the costs of special start-up measures, to use the exchange rate of the European Central Bank of 30 December 2005 for currency conversion (29 CZK = 1 €).</seg>
<seg id="104">Bridges of various types (reinforced concrete, prestressed concrete, steel composite and steel) and various sizes are available on both the D 8 and the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure the comparability of the tested bridge structures, the bridges were grouped according to their design.</seg>
<seg id="106">The analyses also took into account the bridge size within these groups.</seg>
<seg id="107">By far the most common were concrete bridges on both sides of the border (20 bridges on the D 8 and 36 bridges on the A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The study focused on this type of bridge, as the size of the sample allowed the application of mathematical statistical methods and improved the reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The study showed that the m ² price of the concrete bridges on the D 8 / A 17 depends on the bridge size (length, road surface): the larger the bridge, the lower the price per square metre.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the correlation between price and size is more pronounced than for Czech bridges (see illustrations below).</seg>
<seg id="111">On the A 17 two bridges could be found, on the D 8 four bridges with significantly increased price.</seg>
<seg id="112">These bridges were determined partly by a method for detecting significant deviations within a sample and partly by regression analysis of the correlation between bridge price and size (atypically expensive bridges can be identified based on the distance to the regression curve).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, the atypically high price of these bridges should only serve as an indication of which bridges should be concentrated on.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw final conclusions, the causes of the respective high price must be determined in individual cases.</seg>
<seg id="115">This could be due, for example, to uneconomic administrative action, but also to the requirements for protecting the environment or other legitimate reasons.</seg>
<seg id="116">Taking into account the larger average length of Czech concrete bridges compared to the German ones (see table 1), the proven negative correlation between the bridge price and the length suggested that the Czech concrete bridges would be cheaper.</seg>
<seg id="117">This was also supported by the lower labour costs in the Czech Republic compared to Germany.</seg>
<seg id="118">However, the evaluation of the results showed that the price of the concrete bridges on the D 8 is higher than on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="119">During joint meetings, two reasons for this situation were identified:</seg>
<seg id="120">1.</seg>
<seg id="121">In Germany, construction contracts for bridges are mainly awarded separately.</seg>
<seg id="122">This also enables medium-sized companies to participate in the award competition.</seg>
<seg id="123">In the Czech Republic, many bridge buildings are awarded as part of larger contracts for the construction of several kilometres of motorway sections.</seg>
<seg id="124">Orders of this magnitude cannot be handled by medium-sized enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="125">2.</seg>
<seg id="126">In the Czech Republic, the variety of bridge constructions built is greater than in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="127">In this context, the NKò noted that the construction method of bridges is determined long before construction begins,</seg>
<seg id="128">already at the submission of the application for planning approval by the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="129">At this time, it selects a certain bridge construction variant from several alternatives. However, economic efficiency plays a minor role in this decision.</seg>
<seg id="130">Only by means of a thorough analysis of the construction industries of both countries would a final conclusion have been possible with regard to bridge prices in the Czech Republic and Germany. However, this would have gone beyond the scope of this audit.</seg>
<seg id="131">The border bridge is the most expensive steel composite bridge on the D 8 and A 17.</seg>
<seg id="132">The prices for the tunnels on the D 8 are about twice as high as in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="133">However, a comparison of the technical parameters between the tunnels on the D 8 and the tunnels in Germany revealed no significant difference.</seg>
<seg id="134">The significant price differences may be the result of too little competition for tunnels in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="135">However, the small number of tunnels did not allow generalizing conclusions.</seg>
<seg id="136">Economy and effectiveness of the Dresden motorway - Prague</seg>
<seg id="137">The independent Czech Republic was founded in 1993.</seg>
<seg id="138">In the same year, the government adopted the plan for the expansion of the motorway network.</seg>
<seg id="139">It was planned to gradually expand the D 8 from Prague to the state border with Germany.</seg>
<seg id="140">Section 0805 was to be built through the Bohemian Central Uplands before the border section 0807.</seg>
<seg id="141">The Czech Republic finances the D 8 as part of the programme financing.</seg>
<seg id="142">The programme number 327 220 "Construction of the motorway D 8 Prague - Ústí nad Labem - Czech German state border" defines two objectives:</seg>
<seg id="143">1.</seg>
<seg id="144">as a national objective: to improve the link between Prague and Ústi nad Labem;</seg>
<seg id="145">2.</seg>
<seg id="146">as an international destination: the connection between Prague and Berlin as part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV BerlinIstanbul.</seg>
<seg id="147">The programme envisaged completing the construction of the section through the Bohemian Central Uplands in June 2008 and the construction of section 0807 near the border in June 2007.</seg>
<seg id="148">It should be noted that the end of the construction work is not identical to the time of commissioning.</seg>
<seg id="149">The NKò noted that the planning approval decision had already been issued for the construction of the section leading through the Bohemian Central Uplands.</seg>
<seg id="150">Environmental associations have appealed against this decision.</seg>
<seg id="151">A final judgment is still pending.</seg>
<seg id="152">Compared to the schedule provided for in the programme documentation, a delay in the completion of section No.0805 by several years could not be ruled out.</seg>
<seg id="153">In the summer of 2006, the Czech Ministry of Transport proposed a postponement of the completion date of construction phase No.0805 to 2010.</seg>
<seg id="154">As a result, the construction of the border section did not achieve the national goal of improving the connection between Prague and Usti nad Labem.</seg>
<seg id="155">The RMD subjected the border section No. 0807 of the D 8 and section No.0805 through the Bohemian Central Uplands to a profitability study in the years 1999 to 2001.</seg>
<seg id="156">As investment costs, it estimated approximately €639 million for both sections No. 0805 and No. 0807.</seg>
<seg id="157">Table 2: Results of the profitability study (EIRR = internal interest rate)</seg>
<seg id="158">Variant Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="159">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="160">Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="161">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 22 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="162">Opening of all planned motorways and expressways, as well as both D 8 sections in 2007.</seg>
<seg id="163">Traffic volume in the northern part of the border section 25 000 vehicles per day in 2010.</seg>
<seg id="164">The profitability study from 2001 was based on the assumption that the section near the border and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Uplands go under traffic simultaneously.</seg>
<seg id="165">At the time of the examination it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Uplands would not be opened on the original date.</seg>
<seg id="166">This reduces the aforementioned EIRR values.</seg>
<seg id="167">The costs of both sections as at 31.12.2005 were €897 million excluding VAT and thus 27.4% higher than in the profitability assessment 2001.</seg>
<seg id="168">In addition, there is a risk that section 0805 will have a different more complex route, which would affect the profitability of the project.</seg>
<seg id="169">The economic assessment showed that the construction of both motorway sections with a daily traffic volume of at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010 is economically justified.The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22,940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="170">However, a study on diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Central Uplands assumes a traffic volume of 12 600 to 13 750 vehicles per day in 2007. The project is then below the profitability limit.</seg>
<seg id="171">A higher volume of traffic on the routes, which are intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Central Uplands, is highly likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the original profitability study.</seg>
<seg id="172">The aforementioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the border section of the D 8 will not be achieved.</seg>
<seg id="173">The construction of the border section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomical.</seg>
<seg id="174">Also in the construction of the A 17 there were cost increases as in the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="175">As part of the macroeconomic assessment for the Federal Transport Infrastructure Plan 1992, the Federal Ministry responsible for transport assumed investment costs of around €320 million.</seg>
<seg id="176">It thus determined a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.</seg>
<seg id="177">In the meantime, costs have increased to around €670 million and the benefit / cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.</seg>
<seg id="178">Independently of the parallel tests with the NKò in the years 2003 to 2005, the BRH had examined the profitability of the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway.</seg>
<seg id="179">He noted that the authority responsible for the approval demanded an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the course of the examination, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the Road Construction Administration of the superfluity of the landscape tunnel.</seg>
<seg id="181">This avoided €10 million in construction costs and €150,000 in annual operating costs.</seg>
<seg id="182">During the examination of the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction project was inadequately prepared.</seg>
<seg id="183">The following example illustrates this:</seg>
<seg id="184">During the planning phase, the road construction administration refrained from assessing the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschener Wand, as it was difficult to access.</seg>
<seg id="185">Only when the tunnel tunnelling reached the wall did she make up for it.</seg>
<seg id="186">It turned out that the rock was more weathered than assumed in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="187">Complex measures such as anchorages, injections and rockfall protection nets for around €3.3 million were necessary.</seg>
<seg id="188">The road construction administration not only borne the costs for additional, already necessary services such as securing the Dölzschener Wand, but also for those that would not have been necessary in a flawless construction preparation.</seg>
<seg id="189">These include expenses due to disrupted construction processes (€3.2 million), additional training of the tunnelling team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the construction period extension (€7 million).</seg>
<seg id="190">This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is not offset by any lasting added value.</seg>
<seg id="191">The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to better exercise the specialist supervision incumbent on it for major road construction measures.</seg>
<seg id="192">In this context, it should be urged that road construction administrations introduce quality assurance systems.</seg>
<seg id="193">Advantages of cooperation for BRH and NKò The cooperation met the expectations of both courts of auditors.</seg>
<seg id="194">The BRH received insights into the planning, awarding of contracts and execution of the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="195">Both courts of auditors developed a database on bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful in future audits.</seg>
<seg id="196">The NKò found that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and roadway of the D 8 do not differ from those of the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="197">The auditors from both courts of auditors involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience that will be useful in future audits.</seg>
</p>
