<p>
<seg id="1">Public procurement of construction services and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report by the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKò) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">The award of services by public contracting authorities is of great importance for both the state and the economy.</seg>
<seg id="5">The task of the state is to use public funds as economically and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), the procurement of services by public contracting authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In order to ensure largely unrestricted competition across borders, public contracting authorities must comply with EU requirements in their awards above certain value limits (thresholds).</seg>
<seg id="8">To this end, EU member states must transfer and apply EU public procurement law into national law.</seg>
<seg id="9">This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="10">Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.</seg>
<seg id="11">The allocation of benefits is also an area at risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="12">Because of the generally high potential for damage, public contracting authorities must therefore implement appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and inadmissible benefits when awarding their contracts.</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKò) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits on both the EU-wide award of construction services and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="14">The audits focused on the application of EU public procurement law transposed into national regulations as well as the prevention of corruption in the award of construction services in building construction, road construction and transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="15">Awards below the EU thresholds were also included in the considerations with regard to the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit results of both Court of Auditors are summarised in this Joint Report.</seg>
<seg id="17">The report will also be addressed to international institutions, such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Authorities (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="18">Audit areas and audited bodies The evaluations of the Federal Court of Auditors on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional audits, which it carried out in 2011 / 2012 at the construction administrations, which are responsible for the road and building construction of the federal government in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="19">He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and large building projects.</seg>
<seg id="20">In addition, the Federal Court of Auditors drew on results from previous investigations.</seg>
<seg id="21">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from 2008 to 2011. The tests included construction measures in road construction, rail infrastructure construction, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) as well as other construction areas in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the award of federal public contracts is mainly carried out by the building administrations of the federal states.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for procurement in the field of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="24">In building construction, awards are carried out decentrally by those bodies that use state budgetary resources.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, freelancers are also involved in some areas of the procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="26">When comparing the evaluations, differences in public procurement law and the market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.</seg>
<seg id="27">Structure of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to the national sector are regulated by budgetary law and the administrative rules based on it.</seg>
<seg id="30">For both EU-wide and national contracts, many supplementary individual regulations are also provided for by internal administrative provisions,</seg>
<seg id="31">such as the so-called "procurement manuals" of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in more detail in compliance with public procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is subject exclusively to the Procurement Act and other statutory provisions that apply to both above and below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">Procurement law was significantly amended in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new regulation strengthened transparency in the handling of public funds, enabled greater competition and limited the possibilities for corruption in the procurement process.</seg>
<seg id="35">Broad outlines of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">In both countries, EU-wide contracts are subject in particular to the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiated procedure.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, measures below the EU threshold apply to national procurement types (public tender, restricted tender, hands-free procurement), which largely correspond to the aforementioned EU-wide procurement types.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement law in Germany is characterized by the principle of the priority of the open procedure (for contracts to be carried out across the EU) and the public tender (for national contracts).</seg>
<seg id="39">Any interested company can submit an offer in the open procedure and in the public tender process.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another essential feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="41">Above all, the division of an overall construction project into specialist and partial lots serves this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="42">The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.</seg>
<seg id="43">Both of the aforementioned characteristics of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees work in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures also apply to construction projects below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception here is the simplified procedure, in which a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with EU law, Czech public procurement law contains provisions to conclude contracts if competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow the contracting authorities to choose between the open and the non-open procedure.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, including about 1,900 companies with 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Construction volume of public contracting authorities and shares of award types in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In Germany, the total construction volume in 2011 amounted to 307 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="52">Of this, 45.5 billion euros were attributable to public construction (15%), which includes, in addition to federal construction, in particular the construction measures of the federal states and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The construction volume of the federal government in building construction and highway construction (excluding rail infrastructure construction and hydraulic engineering) amounted to 8.5 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="54">The volume of contracts for construction work in the construction and highway construction of the federal government was distributed among the award types in 2011 as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public tenders, 12.7% non-open procedures and restricted tenders and 6.6% negotiation procedures and hands-free awards.</seg>
<seg id="55">Of these, 33.2% were Europe-wide awards.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction projects in the Czech Republic amounted to 4.7 billion euros in 2011, which corresponded to about 25% of the total volume of all construction projects in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, the volume was 7.8 billion euros, which corresponded to 37% of the total construction volume.</seg>
<seg id="58">Breakdown by type of award for 2011: 65.1% open procedures 14.3% non-public procedures 9.5% Negotiation procedures 8.4% simplified procedures for contract volumes below the threshold 2.7% Other procedures</seg>
<seg id="59">The data relate to all public contracts for deliveries, services and construction services awarded by public procurement bodies in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">The above data show that the parallel audits of both countries are directed at a significant proportion of public procurement, the prevention of corruption to be observed in all awards is of great financial importance and that the open procedure and the public tender are of outstanding importance in the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the results of the parallel tests</seg>
<seg id="62">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKò) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits in their countries on the EU-wide award of construction services and corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="63">In this context, the working groups of both Court of Auditors compared the corresponding legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the fields of building construction and road construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">They essentially stated:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU directives on the award of construction services by public contracting authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (points 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">In addition to the EU requirements, the procurement regulations of both countries also serve to prevent corruption, some of which differ in their priorities and details (No. 3.2).</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, an essential requirement for the award documents is that they must contain all the information required for the proper preparation of bids.</seg>
<seg id="68">The performance descriptions must be neutral and must not have any restrictive requirements.</seg>
<seg id="69">In Germany, the award documents have largely met these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, it remains a problem to sufficiently determine the subject of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, construction work must be divided into lots if possible in order to promote competition.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">During its audits, especially in the field of road construction, the NKò found that the award of extensive services without lots or with only very large lots can affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">Restrictions in market potential can result in significant cost increases and carry the risk of price or other agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">Under the provisions of both countries, under certain conditions, the contracting authorities may in principle agree with the companies already commissioned additional or modified services that prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (No. 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">The respective requirements for determining the type of award were largely followed in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="77">According to the regulations of the Czech Republic, procurement bodies are free to choose between open and non-open procedures.</seg>
<seg id="78">In Germany, on the other hand, the statutory and budgetary priority of the open procedure applies to EU-wide awards or public tenders, which corresponds to the open procedure for national awards.</seg>
<seg id="79">This allows more companies to submit offers.</seg>
<seg id="80">This reduces the risk of corruption, makes price fixing between bidders more difficult and leads to the most economical results.</seg>
<seg id="81">For the construction projects whose estimated total contract values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited construction administrations generally awarded the construction work throughout Europe.</seg>
<seg id="82">The correct estimation of the expected contract value is an essential basis for choosing the correct type of award.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, cost databases are used for the cost calculations of public buildings, especially in building construction,</seg>
<seg id="84">which are based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective instrument (No. 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">For construction work to be awarded throughout Europe, preliminary information and announcements must be published. This is intended to strengthen competition by enabling interested companies to adapt to the planned awards at an early stage.</seg>
<seg id="87">The audited building administrations usually adhered to this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or lack of controls may have affected competition (No. 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">The selection of applicants to participate in non-public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="90">Under EU law, the number of invited applicants must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be announced beforehand.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition to the EU requirements, the procurement bodies in both countries should switch as frequently as possible among the companies to be requested when selecting applicants.</seg>
<seg id="93">In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are sometimes very detailed specifications in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="94">The audited administrations did not take these requirements into account in some cases.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, the decisions on the selection of applicants were not always comprehensible (No. 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, in the interest of equal competition, it is necessary to ensure that companies interested in submitting a bid receive the same information during the bid phase.</seg>
<seg id="97">Contact between these companies and with freelancers who were involved in drawing up the service description must be prevented as far as possible in order to avoid anti-competitive agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">However, some of the audited building administrations in Germany did not comply with these requirements (No. 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">When opening up offers, the multi-eye principle and the principle of transparency must be observed in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="101">The requirements for the labelling, documentation, custody and secrecy of the offers are intended to restrict scope for manipulation and are particularly thoroughly defined in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">The tests in both countries revealed only a few complaints (No. 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">Examination and evaluation of the offers are defined in both countries by specifications for the structure and process organisation.</seg>
<seg id="104">The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited procurement bodies.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting agencies handed over offers for examination to third parties without reviewing the offers beforehand and sufficiently documenting abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="106">As a result, the offers were insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (No. 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">At the conclusion of the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies involved in the competition will be informed of the intended contract prior to the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection option also has a preventive function against corruptive behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="109">The Czech Republic also provides for a judicial review option for non-EU procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in a few cases did the award bodies not meet the specified deadlines when awarding orders or deviate from the content of the bidders' offer (No. 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The documentation of the award procedures was not always complete or comprehensible by the audited construction administrations in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in the award notes of some procedures.</seg>
<seg id="113">Some of the deficiencies identified also reduced the corruption-preventive function of the documentation.</seg>
<seg id="114">The public contracting authorities of both countries largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (No. 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Basics of EU public procurement law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="116">EU public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the Procurement Coordination Directive and the Remedies Directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the Member States 8.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general procurement principles of the European Union are in particular the competition requirement, the equal treatment requirement or the prohibition of discrimination as well as the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="119">To enforce these objectives, the Procurement Coordination Directive contains special rules for construction work to be awarded across the EU for construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="120">For this purpose, their estimated order sums must reach or exceed a current volume of 5,000,000 euros.</seg>
<seg id="121">The regulations concern in particular the content of the award documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, compliance with deadlines, including for receipt of tenders, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualifications of applicants and the Remedies Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of applicants and bidders.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of possible violations of public procurement law, affected companies can have the decisions of public contracting authorities reviewed in review proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the directives of the European Union into national law.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">Importance of corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="126">In both countries there is no legal definition of the concept of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="127">In general, corruption is the abuse of a position of trust for private benefit,</seg>
<seg id="128">which is usually initiated by the beneficiaries of these decisions.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.</seg>
<seg id="130">It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of global economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the area of the European Union, the amount of these costs is estimated at 1%.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of public contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair behaviour can call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">They have to review the organisation of their administrations in areas particularly vulnerable to corruption in order to take appropriate safeguards against corruption.</seg>
<seg id="135">Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corruptive abuse.</seg>
<seg id="136">The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly corruption-prone area of work.</seg>
<seg id="137">Corruption prevention measures</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and corruption as well as acceptance and approval of benefits - is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="139">In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a directive and recommendations on corruption12 prevention in the Federal Administration. According to this, in addition to risk analysis, the following principles must be observed for the procurement sector: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi-eye principle and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, award and billing, accurate and complete documentation of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="140">Furthermore, further corruption-preventive requirements have been incorporated into the public procurement rules.</seg>
<seg id="141">For example, the responsible Federal Ministry for Procurement in the area of federal highways introduced an electronically supported control system in 2011,</seg>
<seg id="142">with the award data - such as the estimated costs and the order sums - as well as information on the freelancers involved are collected nationwide and evaluated for abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="143">In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="144">The statutory requirements of transparency and equal treatment of bidders, as well as the prohibition of all discrimination, form the most important foundations of the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper on the fight against corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Some of the measures recommended therein have already been transposed into national public procurement law and corresponding administrative regulations14.</seg>
<seg id="147">The new legislation essentially contains the following rules: reduction of the thresholds for smaller contracts, obligation to prior notification of awards by the award authority, including mention of the grounds for tendering, prohibition of restriction of the number of bidders in non-open proceedings and thus abolition of the possibility of selecting bidders by lottery, introduction of the obligation to publish the contract documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Examination results on the individual phases of the award procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Award documents</seg>
<seg id="150">Award documents The award documents must contain all the information that the bidders need for a proper bid preparation.</seg>
<seg id="151">In particular, the award documents must enable an accurate calculation.</seg>
<seg id="152">No risks may be transferred to the bidders that cannot be calculated for them.</seg>
<seg id="153">The award documents consist in particular of the service description and the contract conditions.</seg>
<seg id="154">In addition, they contain the requirements for proving the qualification (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.</seg>
<seg id="155">Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="156">The requirements of EU law for procurement documents are aimed in particular at the technical specifications.</seg>
<seg id="157">These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should restrict competition as little as possible.</seg>
<seg id="158">The service description must in principle be product-neutral.</seg>
<seg id="159">Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under narrow conditions.</seg>
<seg id="160">Avoiding restrictive requirements in the procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="161">In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the award documents must be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation in the preparation of the offers as well as for manipulation in their evaluation.</seg>
<seg id="162">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="163">Same or similar regulations In both countries, the EU legal requirements on technical specifications have been transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="164">The services are basically product-neutral without brand specifications to tender.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the service descriptions, the individual services must usually be divided into performance units with respective quantities in detail.</seg>
<seg id="166">Prices must be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. euros per m ² or per piece).</seg>
<seg id="167">Only in exceptional cases may services be defined by functional targets.</seg>
<seg id="168">The service descriptions must in any case be complete and unambiguous.</seg>
<seg id="169">They must contain precise quantities and must not include services for which it is not clear whether they are needed.</seg>
<seg id="170">Remuneration according to lump sums or time expenditure must be avoided as far as possible.</seg>
<seg id="171">These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indefinite requirements in the award documents.</seg>
<seg id="172">The service descriptions must enable bidders to prepare their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.</seg>
<seg id="173">The invitation to tender will not be announced until the award documents have been completed.</seg>
<seg id="174">Different regulations</seg>
<seg id="175">There is no obligation to tender for construction work in lots in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="176">If it is possible according to the type of service to be commissioned, the public procurement agencies can divide construction services into several lots.</seg>
<seg id="177">In Germany, construction work is generally divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial) and / or by type or specialist area (specialist).</seg>
<seg id="178">This is intended to enable medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition, expand the number of possible providers and make price fixing more difficult.</seg>
<seg id="179">This type of award is usually considered the most economical.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, evaluation criteria must be indicated in the award documents for both EU-wide and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="181">This should make it completely and conclusively clear to the applicants according to which criteria their offers should be evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="182">In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria in EU-wide announcements, but at the latest in the award documents, is only mandatory for EU-wide procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="183">In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria must only be recorded in an internal administrative award note.</seg>
<seg id="184">Award documents prepared by commissioned freelancers may not contain any references to these offices or planners or experts involved in the building construction and some road construction administrations in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="185">This is to prevent individual companies from obtaining additional information or other inadmissible competitive advantages through contact with these freelancers without the knowledge of the client.</seg>
<seg id="186">This is also the reason why freelancers are not allowed to send award documents or interpret planning documents for inspection.</seg>
<seg id="187">The contact person for the companies is the client alone.</seg>
<seg id="188">There is currently no regulation on this in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="189">Additional or modified services, which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements), are almost always incurred in large construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="190">In both countries, the statutory provisions allow, to a certain extent, the award of supplements to the already commissioned company without a procurement procedure having to be carried out with public notice.</seg>
<seg id="191">According to EU regulations and German regulations, the remuneration of supplementary benefits may not exceed half of the main contract.</seg>
<seg id="192">In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main order without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.</seg>
<seg id="193">In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies to such awards without public announcement.</seg>
<seg id="194">However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the ongoing construction work.</seg>
<seg id="195">If supplementary services are also transferred to the already commissioned company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is generally not possible according to the regulations in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="196">When determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for determining the price of the contract already awarded must be assumed.</seg>
<seg id="197">In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.</seg>
<seg id="198">In the Czech Republic, reduced quantities cannot be offset against additional supplementary benefits.</seg>
<seg id="199">Key audit results</seg>
<seg id="200">BHR</seg>
<seg id="201">Technical specifications and product-neutral tender</seg>
<seg id="202">In individual cases, the service descriptions contained references to national technical approvals or standards that had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.</seg>
<seg id="203">Some service descriptions also contained product-related specifications - for example for graffiti protection, joint tapes or noise protection panels - without this being necessary.</seg>
<seg id="204">In some cases, performance requirements were described so precisely that only one product was eligible.</seg>
<seg id="205">Performance lists subdivided by partial services</seg>
<seg id="206">In none of the examined proceedings has the BRH found any violations of the bid to tender services in principle in a list of services subdivided according to partial services.</seg>
<seg id="207">Completeness of the service descriptions</seg>
<seg id="208">In the vast majority of proceedings, the award documents were completed before the start of the tenders.</seg>
<seg id="209">In some proceedings, the award documents had to be corrected during the offer phase, as some positions or deadlines had changed.</seg>
<seg id="210">Occasionally, the performance lists contained positions where it was not clear whether they were needed.</seg>
<seg id="211">A list of services for demolition work even consisted of almost half of such demand positions.</seg>
<seg id="212">Lots and evaluation criteria</seg>
<seg id="213">Many awards lacked the prescribed justification why the services advertised predominantly according to skilled persons were not further divided into partial lots.</seg>
<seg id="214">There were no complaints when specifying the criteria to be used in the evaluation of the offers.</seg>
<seg id="215">References to freelancers</seg>
<seg id="216">A small part of the service descriptions contained references to the freelancers involved.</seg>
<seg id="217">Their names were partly on the covers or in attached plans or expert opinions.</seg>
<seg id="218">In one case, the registry even explicitly requested applicants to contact the architect "on questions of the tender."</seg>
<seg id="219">Especially in the building construction sector, the contracting authorities attributed the complaints pointed out mainly to failures of the freelancers commissioned with the preparation of the service descriptions.</seg>
<seg id="220">The construction services pointed out the lack of capacity in order to be able to sufficiently control the performance descriptions.</seg>
<seg id="221">NKò</seg>
<seg id="222">Technical specifications and product-neutral tender In the public procurement for the construction of a residential building with 12 residential units, a supplier and a specific product brand were specified in the service description.</seg>
<seg id="223">The contracting authority did not allow the use of comparable products without justifying this.</seg>
<seg id="224">During the construction of several university buildings, suppliers and products were also specified in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="225">Performance descriptions with performance units</seg>
<seg id="226">In the case of construction projects in some industrial areas, the contracting authority did not clearly specify the scope and type of services required in the service descriptions.</seg>
<seg id="227">As performance units, it only specified the converted space of the individual buildings in cubic metres.</seg>
<seg id="228">Completeness of the service descriptions</seg>
