<seg id="597">Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="598">The EU's guidelines provide for a multi-stage procedure:</seg>
<seg id="599">First of all, the suitability of the bidders must be determined.</seg>
<seg id="600">Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.</seg>
<seg id="601">Companies that are legally convicted of bribery or fraud offences, for example, must be excluded from participation in the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="602">The offers of the non-excluded bidders must be checked mathematically, technically and economically and evaluated on the basis of the previously announced award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="603">The client has to determine the most economically favourable offer. The client has to examine offers with unusually low prices in particular.</seg>
<seg id="604">The examination and evaluation of the tenders is a particularly manipulation-prone phase of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="605">For example, bidders can be unjustifiably excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements can be left in competition.</seg>
<seg id="606">By preferring or disadvantaging bidders, the valuation result can be inadmissibly impaired and thus the determination of the most economically favourable offer can be prevented.</seg>
<seg id="607">The registry must therefore take special precautions to ensure that the persons charged with the examination and evaluation meet the requirements for integrity and expertise.</seg>
<seg id="608">It must also ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure and the decisions taken.</seg>
<seg id="609">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="610">Same or similar regulations</seg>
<seg id="611">In accordance with EU requirements, the offers in both countries must be examined and evaluated in multi-stage procedures.</seg>
