<seg id="695">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="696">The regulations for the examination and evaluation of bids in both countries comply with EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="697">However, for details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective regulations differ from each other.</seg>
<seg id="698">In Germany, the procedure is more strongly regulated by detailed requirements, in particular for the implementation of the multi-eyes principle and for the protection of offers, than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the specifications on the basis of which the adequacy of the prices offered must be checked.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, some of the audited procurement procedures found that essential procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of the bids were not or only insufficiently documented.</seg>
<seg id="701">Without traceability and transparency of the audit and evaluation decisions, however, possible manipulative interventions are favoured.</seg>
<seg id="702">A particularly serious defect was the handover of all offers to third parties without the public contracting authority having sufficiently reviewed and documented the offers beforehand, thereby protecting them from possible manipulation in further proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="703">If public contracting authorities have tasks carried out in the examination and evaluation of the offers by third parties, sufficient precautions and an increased control effort are required to counter the increased risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="704">When checking the adequacy of prices, the audited services in Germany did not always make full use of the specified instruments and insufficiently examined the price structure of the offers.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, complaints arose mainly in the aptitude test and in the application of the evaluation criteria.</seg>
