<seg id="737">Letters of order according to open proceedings also contained content deviating from the content of the offer in individual cases, such as changed dates.</seg>
<seg id="738">In several cases, the clients did not comply with the award deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="739">In an open procedure, a contracting authority therefore awarded the contract for the second cheapest offer, as a company with a 50% cheaper offer was no longer prepared to carry out the services at the originally offered price after the award period expired.</seg>
<seg id="740">NKò</seg>
<seg id="741">In the case of a construction project in the university sector, the contracting authority deviated from the bidder's offer in terms of content.</seg>
<seg id="742">In some contracts, for example in the construction of road maintenance, in the construction of a motorway and a bypass, the contracting authorities concluded the contracts after the expiry of the statutory deadline.</seg>
<seg id="743">When awarding construction work for the rehabilitation of former military premises, the award authority forwarded the notification of the award of the contract to all bidders only after the expiry of the statutory deadline.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented the EU's guidelines for the conclusion of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="746">The legal protection of losing candidates or bidders increases the tools for preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The scope of legal protection in Czech public procurement law is also extended to contracts below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, the deadlines for awarding contracts were exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">Construction administrations should avoid the shortcomings identified in the completion of their procurement procedures in future.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The award procedures must be documented in a comprehensible manner during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings and the justifications of the individual decisions.</seg>
<seg id="753">In EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made known.</seg>
<seg id="754">The order data are also recorded in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption The documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="756">A carefully and promptly prepared documentation only enables the traceability of the award decisions.</seg>
<seg id="757">In particular, it also serves the effective legal protection of bidders when awarding contracts above the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of avoiding corruption, as the compulsion to justify award decisions in detail significantly restricts scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">The notice of a contract awarded in an EU-wide procurement procedure must be submitted by the respective procurement authority to the EU Official Publications Office within 48 days.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the announcements in the Official Journal of the EU and thus also implements the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The procurement bodies must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the competent national ministries of the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the EU Commission produces annual EU statistics through which it can obtain an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.</seg>
<seg id="763">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar regulations</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed EU documentation and reporting requirements into national law.</seg>
<seg id="766">The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Different regulations</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the publication obligation for contracts awarded is not limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notice period is shortened to 15 days.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, in addition to EU-wide awards, there is a publication obligation only for restricted tenders and for free-handed awards from value limits of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros without VAT (so-called ex-post transparency).</seg>
<seg id="771">Below these value limits and in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition procedure receive information on the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="772">Key audit results</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of the audited award procedures were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The award notes did not contain all the necessary information, such as the justification of product specifications or references to national regulations.</seg>
<seg id="777">In a procurement procedure, the award authority did not justify why it awarded the contract to a company, although its offer did not contain mandatory evidence.</seg>
<seg id="778">In a few cases, the documents of the award bodies did not contain all the evidence required for the documentation of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="779">Announcements about order awards</seg>
<seg id="780">In some EU-wide procurement procedures, procurement bodies failed to make the award of contracts known.</seg>
<seg id="781">Further award procedures lacked evidence that the award bodies had announced the contracts awarded.</seg>
<seg id="782">Reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistical statements viewed contained the required minimum information. They had been prepared and sent on schedule.</seg>
<seg id="784">Ex-post transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the audited construction administrations published the contract data of the completed procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="786">However, a building administration did not publish this data due to a transmission error.</seg>
<seg id="787">The building administration only noticed this error after half a year,</seg>
<seg id="788">so that the contract data of the award procedures completed so far have not been published.</seg>
<seg id="789">NKò</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">In the case of construction measures for the organisation of a major sporting event, the documentation of the award procedures showed considerable deficiencies, mainly incorrect information, such as incorrect offer prices in the minutes of the evaluation commissions.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some minutes of the offer openings were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Announcements about order awards</seg>
<seg id="794">In several road construction projects, announcements about awarded contracts were only published late or not at all.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="796">The regulations on documentation and reporting and reporting obligations are largely consistent in both countries and implement EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="797">In principle, this ensures the transparency of procurement procedures, including the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="798">The regulations to be applied for publication in the Czech Republic go slightly further than the requirements in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="799">The deficiencies in documentation and announcements identified significantly restricted the corruption-preventive effect of these instruments in the respective procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Construction administrations should further improve the transparency of their procurement procedures and contract awards and fully comply with their reporting and reporting obligations.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits of the NKò and the BRH have focused on two priorities that are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of construction services by public contracting authorities: the application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">EU law enables cross-border competition to create a European internal market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Corruption prevention measures not only serve to avoid or at least reduce corruption, but also to avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two Court of Auditors on the application of public procurement regulations in both countries and the comparison of these regulations provide information on similarities and differences that can be helpful for both countries in the further development of their public procurement law and its application.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement rules</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed the EU's requirements for the award of construction services into national law.</seg>
<seg id="809">This gives the Czech Republic and Germany an important common basis for awarding construction services and taking into account the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">The construction administrations of both countries have partly supported these bids very extensively by further administrative regulations.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has largely transferred the requirements for construction work to be awarded across the EU to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the investigations by the Court of Auditors have shown that the construction administrations have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.</seg>
<seg id="813">The building administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the complaints identified when implementing the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">The audits in the Czech Republic have mainly highlighted risks that affect the profitability of the contracts.</seg>
<seg id="815">For example, incomplete service descriptions made additional services necessary, which were often awarded in violation of legislation. Moreover, the cost calculations were usually inadequately prepared. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of possible bidders and restricted competition, especially in the case of transport buildings.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The investigations did not aim to uncover cases of corruption,</seg>
<seg id="818">also because the Court of Auditors do not have the appropriate instruments for this.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, the Court of Auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the award of construction services and how these requirements are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">Both countries have set different priorities when it comes to preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="821">Above all, the German regulations provide for largely unlimited competition as well as transparency and controls as central elements of the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech regulations are primarily aimed at increasing the transparency of procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction services and are geared towards their special requirements.</seg>
<seg id="826">In some cases, the relevant regulations specify very precisely how the requirements for the prevention of corruption must be taken into account in the course of the procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the opinion of the BRH, in particular, the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tender is a suitable instrument for significantly reducing the risk of corruption in the award of construction services. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative intervention.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analyses and sufficient controls (especially the multi-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures as well as various organisational measures are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore sees no fundamental need to change the corresponding requirements of the administrations in the award of construction services.</seg>
<seg id="830">The rules on the prevention of corruption are largely taken into account in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The shortcomings identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some benchmarks.</seg>
<seg id="832">Construction administrations should further train their employees on the requirements for corruption prevention and raise their awareness of this problem even more.</seg>
<seg id="833">A substantial part of the complaints related to tasks that the building administrations had delegated to freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="834">Without controls and sufficient safeguards, however, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.</seg>
<seg id="835">Tasks at risk of manipulation and corruption should therefore only be transferred to third parties if the administration can ensure a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interventions.</seg>
<seg id="836">NKò</seg>
<seg id="837">The Czech Republic adopted a strategy against corruption at government level, in which the area of public procurement is the most important component.</seg>
<seg id="838">The Procurement Act and the associated implementing provisions have been substantially amended.</seg>
<seg id="839">The audits of the NKò took place during the implementation of this strategy.</seg>
<seg id="840">The adopted strategy and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures, as the procurement bodies must justify the profitability of the contract awards, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the nature of the evaluations, and properly document and publish all these aspects.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">The NKò and the BRH generally assess the implementation of the EU guidelines positively.</seg>
<seg id="843">The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU imperatives of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at enabling and promoting cross-border competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">In view of the enormous material and ideological damage potential caused by manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both courts of auditors see the construction administrations in their countries demanded to continue their measures against corruption and manipulation and, if necessary, to improve them.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organisation and procedures of the procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to take appropriate countermeasures.</seg>
<seg id="847">The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open proceedings in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures can provide a broader area for competition and significantly reduce the risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="848">A stronger division of construction services into lots can also have a favourable impact on offer prices, provided that it achieves greater competition with a higher number of bidders.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for the efficient procurement of public contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised construction administrations. In the Czech Republic, on the other hand, these tasks - with the exception of transport construction projects - are carried out by the departments themselves or contractors commissioned by them.</seg>
<seg id="851">The Court of Auditors of both countries intend, even after the completion of their joint project, to further develop the findings that are important to them and, if necessary, to bring them to the parliament and government of their country.</seg>
<seg id="852">Both Court of Auditors are also convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at international level to the International Organization of Supreme Audit Authorities (INTOSAI), because the principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to effectively counter corruption and to ensure the economic procurement of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.</seg>
<seg id="853">Annexes</seg>
</p>
