<p>
<seg id="1">Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the audit</seg>
<seg id="3">Preface</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are the main source of income for public budgets.</seg>
<seg id="5">One focus of the activities of the Court of Auditors should therefore be on examining this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">This applies in particular to VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">This alone creates annual tax losses of an estimated 100 billion euros1 in the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="8">Already at the VI. EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn, the participants pointed out the need for enhanced cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">This enables the Court of Auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and optimise audit practice.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="11">In 2006, the Court of Auditors of both countries audited for the first time in parallel in the area of VAT.</seg>
<seg id="12">The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">Since VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the Court of Auditors is needed, enabling a comprehensive assessment of whether the measures taken are suitable for effectively countering VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two Court of Auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany Report on the audit</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Induction</seg>
<seg id="16">Examination number: (CZ) 09 / 11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of audit: (CZ) Administration of VAT (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NKò), audit</seg>
<seg id="18">Examination objective:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The VAT administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. Furthermore, the procedures applied by the tax authorities in intergovernmental assistance should be examined.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit was intended to evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="21">In addition, further examination fields - linked to the VAT - should be processed.</seg>
<seg id="22">The findings made should be compared to determine whether taxation procedures can be optimised.</seg>
<seg id="23">The examination period was the years 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the examination period until the conclusion of the examination.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination</seg>
<seg id="25">The Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on a control audit for the administration of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the previous parallel audit, they had uncovered suspected cases involving intra-Community turnover,</seg>
<seg id="27">which made a repeated examination appear appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="28">Based on the audit findings, the two courts of auditors made recommendations on the administration of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The aim of the review was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented and to investigate the suspected cases identified.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also dealt with other issues, including selected cases of high-risk intra-Community turnover, mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of VAT claims and the VAT audit of large enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="31">The Court of Auditors found:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous examination</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: Regulations for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">During the first audit, the Court of Auditors compared the registration procedures for VAT in the two states and found differences that caused problems.</seg>
<seg id="35">The Court of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This has also been taken up at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798 / 2003 provides for the extension of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of VAT obligations.</seg>
<seg id="38">The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their possible deletion.</seg>
<seg id="39">The Court of Auditors expected Member States, in accordance with their decision in principle, to agree on appropriate arrangements to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">Member States reached political agreement on the final version of the draft in ECOFIN.</seg>
<seg id="41">The aforementioned common rules are no longer included, and the two Court of Auditors regret that.</seg>
<seg id="42">They still consider such regulations to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary notifications As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended to Member States that summary notifications (CMs) should be submitted monthly in future.</seg>
<seg id="44">The amounts of intra-Community turnover could then be reviewed more promptly.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common VAT system for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for surrendering the ZM to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the implementation did not enter into force until 1 July 2010. It has thus not transposed the obligation to submit the ZM monthly into national law on time.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Data comparison of VAT pre-registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the merging of the procedures for VAT pre-registrations and ZM The German financial administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Court of Auditors and set up a working group to develop possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="49">The work has not yet been completed.</seg>
<seg id="50">The Federal Court of Auditors will monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level In the course of the initial audit, the two Court of Auditors agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria as well as elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems with both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Court of Auditors focused on German participation in the "Platform for Risk Management."</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Control audit of selected intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the first audit, the Court of Auditors had jointly examined turnover in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been executed or which had been declared differently by the taxpayers of the two states in the VAT pre-registrations (or VAT declarations) or ZM.</seg>
<seg id="58">The Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the audit.</seg>
<seg id="59">The audits by the tax offices (FÄ) of both states had not yet been completed at the conclusion of the first parallel audit.</seg>
<seg id="60">The audit revealed that the tax procedures for these selected sales have now been completed. The respective financial administrations had taken appropriate measures to this end (including subsequent VAT fixes or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community turnover</seg>
<seg id="62">The audit also included highly risky intra-Community transactions between taxpayers in the EU covered by the EUROCANET system.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET serves to identify risky taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.</seg>
<seg id="65">The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the data exchange within the framework of EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="66">From the point of view of an active participating state, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">As a result, no information could be obtained about which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.</seg>
<seg id="68">The NKU found both normal business transactions and those with suspicion of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected sales.</seg>
<seg id="69">The FÄ were only able to examine high-risk sales to a limited extent. This applied in particular to so-called "missing traders," whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">In case of suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports</seg>
<seg id="71">It is recommended that customs and tax authorities work more closely together to track the identity of goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany and a number of other countries have rejected active participation in EUROCANET because, from their point of view, there is no sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">The Federal Court of Auditors found that the German financial administration uses other instruments to identify risky taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="74">Nevertheless, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation:</seg>
<seg id="76">was created by EUROFISC.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should be incorporated into the planned network to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4.Mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are processed in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="81">The Federal Court of Auditors and the NKU compared the statistics that both Member States submitted to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">These statistics contained discrepancies.</seg>
<seg id="83">The two Court of Auditors consider a renewed discussion on statistics at EU level to be useful in order to avoid any discrepancies that still exist in the future.</seg>
<seg id="84">If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used adequately for comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">Both Court of Auditors believe that Member States with a low recovery rate should strive to achieve at least the average recovery rate.</seg>
<seg id="88">The Commission should assist Member States in this if desired.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. VAT testing for large enterprises</seg>
<seg id="90">The Court of Auditors analysed the legal situation regarding the VAT audit of large enterprises in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the financial administrations that they considered important in this context.</seg>
<seg id="92">It became clear that the situation in both countries is different.</seg>
<seg id="93">The CZ has a system for selecting risky cases that incorporates a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data and profit and loss statements).</seg>
<seg id="94">Overall, VAT control can be effectively controlled and analysed.</seg>
<seg id="95">A special tax office for large enterprises is to be set up in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">There is no comparable system in Germany yet. This makes it difficult to control and analyse VAT control as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="97">The German financial administration focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the VAT pre-registrations or VAT declarations and the ZM.</seg>
<seg id="98">Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Examination procedure</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Examination proceedings in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">Department II - State Budget Revenue and Regional Departments IX Pilsen, X České Budějovice, XIII Brno and XV Ostrava audited between May 2009 and February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="102">Audited bodies were the Czech Ministry of Finance and 25 FÄ: Tax Office (FA) Brno II, FA Brno III, FA Brno IV, FA in Břeclav, FA in Domažlice, FA in Hodonín, FA in Hradec Králové, FA in Cheb, FA in Jablonec nad Nisou, FA in Karlovy Vary, FA in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FA in Kraslice, FA Ostrava I, FA Ostrava III, FA in Písek, FA in Pilsen, FA Prague 1, FA Prague 4, FA Prague 8, FA in Rakovník, FA</seg>
<seg id="103">The Senate of the Czech Court of Auditors approved the audit findings on 27 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 Examination proceedings in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">The examination area traffic taxes and employees of the assigned PÄB Berlin, Frankfurt / Main and Munich examined from February 2009 to February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="106">After selecting the example cases, they announced the examination in several countries:</seg>
<seg id="107">• Bavaria, • Hamburg, • Hesse, • North Rhine-Westphalia, • Saxony. They also conducted interviews at the Federal Ministry of Finance (Federal Ministry of Finance).</seg>
<seg id="108">Tax files from the following FÄ were included in the audit: • Erlangen, Zentralfinanzamt München, Hof, Schwandorf, Regensburg, Weiden in der Oberpfalz, Grafenau; • Hamburg-Nord, Hamburg-Hansa, Sonderfinanzamt Hamburg for large companies; • Wiesbaden I, Wiesbaden II, Darmstadt; • Essen-NordOst, FA Essen for tax audits at large companies and corporations, Lüdenscheid; • Chemnitz-Süd.</seg>
<seg id="109">In addition, talks were held with the FÄ Mühlacker, Reutlingen, Starnberg, Verden, Erfurt, Leipzig, Halle-Süd and the OFD Frankfurt / Main, Chemnitz and Münster.</seg>
<seg id="110">The Federal Court of Auditors informed the Federal Ministry of Finance of the audit results in April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="111">3.3 Cooperation between the two Court of Auditors</seg>
<seg id="112">Prior to the parallel audit, the representatives of both Court of Auditors met in September 2008 to discuss and define the audit topics.</seg>
<seg id="113">In December 2008, the Presidents of both Court of Auditors signed the agreement on cooperation in the parallel audit.</seg>
<seg id="114">At a meeting in June 2009 in Bonn, the examination teams briefed on the initial results obtained during the exam preparation, discussed possible examination approaches and agreed on how to proceed.</seg>
<seg id="115">A second meeting took place in Prague from 2 to 4 December 2009.</seg>
<seg id="116">The audit teams exchanged the audit findings obtained so far and agreed on the schedule for the preparation of the joint audit report.</seg>
<seg id="117">The two Court of Auditors identified the following topics for their parallel audit: • Evaluation of the recommendations made in the previous report; • Review of selected cases of intra-Community transactions between taxpayers from the CZ and Germany, which could not be fully clarified during the first parallel audit; • Review of selected intra-Community transactions classified as risky between taxpayers from the CZ and Germany; • Examination of the procedures of the two tax administrations regarding intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of VAT claims; • VAT audits at large companies.</seg>
<seg id="118">The report on the results of the parallel audit was prepared during a working meeting in June 2010.</seg>
<seg id="119">4. Examination of the administration of VAT in selected areas</seg>
<seg id="120">4.1 Implementation of the recommendations from the first joint examination</seg>
<seg id="121">4.1.1 Implementation of recommendations in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="122">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="123">Harmonisation of the conditions for the registration of taxpayers within the EU Supported</seg>
<seg id="124">on the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors has recommended adjusting the requirements for VAT registration and introducing new rules for the cancellation of registration in the CZ.</seg>
