<seg id="580">• Are high-result examination fields recorded?</seg>
<seg id="581">CZ: Yes, the FA can select examination cases based on criteria linked to selected indicators stored in the ATIS system.</seg>
<seg id="582">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="583">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and VAT special auditors do not provide such information.</seg>
<seg id="584">However, the finance ministries of the federal and state governments have agreed on a common approach.</seg>
<seg id="585">Accordingly, auditors and tax investigators of the federal states must enter the additional tax result they achieve if a certain threshold is exceeded in ZAUBER.</seg>
<seg id="586">In this case, supplementary information must be provided, e.g. on the origin of the additional VAT result achieved.</seg>
<seg id="587">• What are the most common findings?</seg>
<seg id="588">CZ:</seg>
<seg id="589">- Large taxable enterprises have unjustifiably claimed input tax deduction for purchased deliveries and services,</seg>
<seg id="590">• which were not used for an entrepreneurial activity according to § 72 (1) CZ UStG;</seg>
<seg id="591">• which were used for representation expenses according to § 75 (3) CZ UStG;</seg>
<seg id="592">• due to invoices that do not meet the requirements of § 73 (1) CZ UStG</seg>
<seg id="593">- Large taxable enterprises have omitted the registration of VAT to be paid in § 21 (1) CZ UStG.</seg>
<seg id="594">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="595">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and VAT special auditors do not provide such information.</seg>
<seg id="596">Findings on VAT from audits of large enterprises are not recorded separately by the countries.</seg>
<seg id="597">However, the Federal Central Tax Office can evaluate the ZAUBER database into which auditors and tax investigators of the federal states have to enter the additional tax result they achieve if a certain threshold is exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="598">• Does the financial administration analyse high-results audit fields and draw consequences for strategic management?</seg>
<seg id="599">CZ: Yes, for example, nationwide audits are carried out with regard to risky goods and industries.</seg>
<seg id="600">Germany: There are no regulations at the federal level.</seg>
<seg id="601">Accordingly, the statistics compiled at the federal level for auditors and VAT special auditors do not provide information on particularly "productive" audit fields.</seg>
<seg id="602">With regard to the analysis of such information, the benefits and manner of its further use, there were different views among the survey bodies.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some Chief Financial Directorates provide such information to the FÄ, but the FÄ are free to use it or not.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">As a result, large amounts of information are processed automatically in the CZ. Among other things, data from VAT audits, as well as key figures from balance sheets, profit and loss statements are processed in the system.</seg>
<seg id="606">The CZ is able to manage the selection of risky cases based on a wide range of information.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the evaluation and management of VAT tests in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In the CZ, the establishment of a special tax office for large enterprises is planned for 2012.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the financial administration does not collect comparably large amounts of data.</seg>
<seg id="610">Accordingly, it is more difficult to fulfil these tasks in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="611">The emphasis is more on the selection of relevant individual cases.</seg>
<seg id="612">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of the information in VAT pre-registrations or VAT declarations as well as test instructions, qualified auditors select the cases to be examined and ensure the correct taxation.</seg>
<seg id="614">In order to reduce VAT revenue losses and at the same time increase the risk of being detected for unreliable entrepreneurs, appropriate management processes and risk management systems must be introduced.</seg>
<seg id="615">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="616">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusions</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation between the two Court of Auditors has proved its worth.</seg>
<seg id="619">This made it possible to gain necessary insights into the systems applied in both countries: in particular: • Intra-Community turnover, • Risk management at VAT in particular with regard to the selection of risky turnover, • Recovery of VAT receivables and • VAT audit of large enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="620">The audit revealed differences in strategies for detecting VAT fraud and in the systems explained above.</seg>
<seg id="621">These findings can be used to improve existing procedures.</seg>
<seg id="622">They can also be used to initiate a discussion among interested bodies on which audit approaches and strategies can be used to combat fraud, such as the relationship within and between the Member States and the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="623">The experience and insights gained should encourage us to continue to jointly examine the administration of VAT in the future.</seg>
<seg id="624">6. Communique</seg>
<seg id="625">The report was prepared in Czech, English and German and signed by the Presidents of the Czech Court of Auditors and the Federal Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="626">Status of information: June 2010.</seg>
